  "text": "It is obvious from the above considerations that the above theory is unconstrained in the sense of Dirac [21] . It may be important to emphasize here that an unconstrained system like the above theory is a gauge-noninvariant theory and it is some what akin to a gauge-fixed gauge-invariant theory which makes it a gauge-noninvariant system. In the presence of a scalar dilaton field the theory of course, becomes a constrained system in the sense of Dirac as shown in our earlier work [CITATION_1] . For further details of the IFQ of this theory we refer to our earleir work of Ref. [CITATION_2] .",
